, with clubs they tried to crowd in more and more, but there was indeed no more room. We had eighty-one in our car. In other cars, where they were luckier, they had possibly only seventy-five. There may have been cars with as many as eighty-five. At any rate the average load for each wagon was about eighty people."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1064.647","u": "Were these the French forty-and-eight cars?"},    {"who": "Jaques Matzner", "start": "1068.417","u": "They were French cattle cars."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1070.674","u": "Yes. Forty-and-eight."},    {"who": "Jaques Matzner", "start": "1072.299","u": "I don&#39;t know"},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1073.361","u": "Those &#34;forty men and eight horses.&#34;"},    {"who": "Jaques Matzner", "start": "1077.092","u": "Oh, yes, yes. That is correct. Forty person or eight&#226;quarante hommes ou huit chevaux."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1081.726","u": "Yes."},    {"who": "Jaques Matzner", "start": "1082.659","u": "That was the inscription. We traveled about five days and five nights without interruption. That is, the train stopped several times, but we never knew where we were. We got no nourishment. We received not a single drop of water. There wasn&#39;t a single hygienic convenience in our car, nothing for a man to satisfy his needs. We managed as we could, during this trip to Kosel. In Kosel the train stopped. During this time we had nine deaths, three women, four men, and two children. In Kosel the train stopped. We had to disembark-not all of us, only the men between sixteen and forty-five. All men older than that, and in general all the women, had to remain in the cars."},    {"who": "David Boder", "start": "1144.603","u": "Were you married?"},    {"who": "Jaques Matzner", "start": "1145.996","u": "No, I was not married. And I was among those who jumped out. To say jumped out is an exaggeration, because we could hardly move by then. I remember clearly that while I was